The executive order issued on December 21, 2018, focuses on the management of forests, rangelands, and other Federal lands to reduce the risk of catastrophic wildfires. The order emphasizes the need for active vegetation management and partnerships with states, tribes, communities, non-profit organizations, and the private sector. It acknowledges the challenges associated with regulatory analysis and consultation requirements that often delay active management. The order sets goals for the Secretaries of the Interior and Agriculture to develop plans for wildfire prevention activities, including reducing fuel loads, protecting water quality, and treating invasive species. It also emphasizes the importance of coordination, efficient processes, and the use of unmanned aerial systems. The Secretaries are instructed to develop a wildfire strategy to support local land managers and prioritize actions to protect habitats, communities, and infrastructure. The order encourages collaboration with states, tribes, communities, non-profit organizations, and the private sector to reduce fuel loads and improve land conditions.